OUTLINE TERMS OF REFERENCE FOR CONSULTANTS 

1.  The consulting team for the technical assistance (TA) will comprise three international 
and  four  domestic  consultants,  recruited  on  an  individual  basis,  in  accordance  with  the 
Guidelines  on  the  Use  of  Consultants  of  the  Asian  Development  Bank  (ADB)  and  other 
arrangements satisfactory to ADB for the engagement of domestic consultants. Each consultant 
is required to work with the team in developing all outputs. The team will coordinate closely with 
other ongoing ADB activities in the area of governance like the access to justice program, the 
devolution support program, devolved social services (Sindh), and especially the Balochistan 
public resource management program. The consultants will take into account the relevant ADB 
guidelines and requirements, especially on poverty and social analysis, and ADB's Policy on 
Gender and Development. The specific technical tasks associated with each consultant are 
outlined in the following paragraphs. 

A.  Governance and Institutional Development Specialist, and Team Leader  (domestic, 
5 person-months) 

2.  The team leader will be a governance and institutional development specialist or the 
equivalent, with at least 10 years of experience in public sector reform and decentralization and 
institutional development. The specialist will be familiar with crosscutting issues of poverty 
reduction, gender, and environmental concerns. The specialist will 

(i)  lead the TA with the program director and team coleader;  
(ii)  prepare a task matrix for consultants and counterparts; 
(iii)  prepare a problem tree, a capacity constraint analysis, and program framework; 
(iv)  prepare a situation analysis and review alternative approaches to strengthening 
devolution and governance in Balochistan; 
(v)  propose monitoring and evaluating arrangements; 
(vi)  coordinate closely with other ongoing ADB activities in the area of governance, 
like  the  access-to-justice program, the devolution support program, devolved 
social  services  (Sindh),  and  (especially)  the  public  resource  management 
program; 
(vii)  with the help of the sector specialists, propose a set of district performance 
indicators to be used for performance-based budgeting; 
(viii)  identify key issues in public social sector performance and reform requirements;   
(ix)  identify systemic barriers to decentralization as a risk;  
(x)  determine  provincial,  district,  tehsil  municipal  administrations  and  community 
roles and capacity requirements for social sector management; 
(xi)  evaluate the best modality for the program and project; 
(xii)  investigate the reason for an integrated program; 
(xiii)  review  current  devolution  practices  that  support  social  service  delivery,  and 
identify governance support required for social sector development; 
(xiv)  review  international  and  local  experience,  including  of  ADB,  with  improving 
governance and finance in the sector; 
(xv)  lead the design of the local government support structure and program; 
(xvi)  prepare arrangements for implementing the program, specifying responsibilities 
for all stakeholders, including the local governments, line departments, steering 
committee, and program implementation unit; and prepare terms of reference; 
(xvii)  with help from sector specialists, identify key sector policy reforms relating to 
service delivery at the district level and prepare the policy matrix for the program; 
(xviii)  consult district administrators to refine procedures for sector-specific guidelines 
and instruments to improve service delivery;

