(xix)  plan capacity building to strengthen governance and prepare action plans; with 
district social sector staff, develop plans and procedures to work closely at local 
government levels, including community citizen boards and school management 
committees, to improve the accountability of service delivery; 
(xx)  review possible environmental aspects of the interventions and, if  necessary, 
propose measures to mitigate risks; and 
(xxi)  prepare the technical feasibility study, according to ADB format and the draft 
program implementation manual. 

B.  Economist/Financial Expert and Team Coleader (domestic, 5 person-months)  

3.  The  consultant  will  be  an  economist  or  financial  expert  with  at  least  5  years  of 
experience with reforms in the public sector in Pakistan. The consultant will 

(i)  co-coordinate the team with the program director and the team leader;  
(ii)  help the team leader to prepare the technical feasibility study, according to ADB 
format and the draft program implementation manual; 
(iii)  review sector financing based on work carried out by the Balochistan government 
and ADB; 
(iv)  make sure that the following issues are addressed: availability of resources, 
resource transfer; and incentive structure for service providers; and that clients 
can take advantage of services;  
(v)  work  closely  with  the  Balochistan  Resource  Management  Program  (BRMP) 
team; 
(vi)  review the overall budget and financing of local government administration; 
(vii)  review possibilities of cost recovery; 
(viii)  estimate district social sector financing requirements based on several models, 
propose financing arrangements for devolved social services, and prepare a 
detailed report;  
(ix)  determine major sources and uses of funds for each social sector, drawing on 
existing information from budgets and projects; 
(x)  propose approaches for improving the allocation and use of funds; 
(xi)  assess general recurrent cost implications of various types of social services 
delivery mechanisms and propose ways to sustain their impact; 
(xii)  prepare a draft provincial and district medium-term expenditure plan to improve 
social  sector  outcome,  including  the  potential  for  private  sector  financing  in 
coordination  with  the  poverty  reduction  strategy  program  (PRSP)  and  other 
related assistance to avoid duplication;  
(xiii)  prepare and summarize the outcomes of an economic analysis according to ADB 
guidelines, including program rationale, justification, and information on cost-
effectiveness and rate of returns for the various sectors; and 
(xiv)  prepare estimates of the costs of the policy reform agenda. 

C.  Public-Private Partnership Expert (domestic, 4 person-months) 

4.  The expert will be a sociologist or equivalent, with at least 5 years’ experience in 
nongovernment  organization  (NGO)  involvement  in  the  provision  of  social  services,  and 
administrative handling of NGO-Government cooperation. The expert will 

(i)  assist the team to prepare a task matrix for the international consultants, program 
framework, and problem-tree analysis that captures critical constraints;

14  Appendix 4 
(ii)  together with the sector specialists, identify areas and tasks where NGO and 
private  sector  involvement  will  be  appropriate  and  likely  can  improve  the 
availability and quality of services; 
(iii)  identify  models  of  public-private  partnership  (PPP)  in  Pakistan  and  lessons 
learned; 
(iv)  review  existing  laws,  regulations  and  contracting  modalities  of  existing  PPP 
models; 
(v)  with the input from team members, identify a PPP model that is supporting social 
participation by beneficiaries of basic social services, and that could be adapted 
in rural Balochistan; 
(vi)  draft regulations and rules for NGO and private sector involvement; 
(vii)  draft model contracts for outsourcing of public tasks; 
(viii)  elaborate  monitoring  and  evaluation  tools  for  NGO  and  private  sector 
involvement; 
(ix)  meet with NGOs and discuss their availability and capacity to be involved in 
service delivery in Balochistan; 
(x)  assist  the  finance  and  economics  specialist  to  prepare  the  final  report  by 
providing the policies, and financial and implementation arrangements required 
for PPP to improve social services; 
(xi)  assist ADB in any other assignments as may be reasonably expected within the 
scope of work; 

D.  Gender and Social Participation Expert (domestic, 3 person-months).  

5.  The expert will be a sociologist or equivalent, with at least 5 years’ experience in social, 
gender, and poverty analysis; participatory planning; and hands-on community development. 
The expert will 

(i)  take into account the work done under the BRMP project preparatory TA; 
(ii)  assist the team to prepare a task matrix for the international consultants, program 
framework, and problem-tree analysis that captures critical constraints; 
(iii)  prepare a poverty map based on district indicators for use as a base line for 
program  interventions,  in  coordination  with  the  PRSP  and  other  related 
assistance, to avoid duplication; 
(iv)  appraise  district poverty assessments and any special issues for vulnerable 
groups; 
(v)  conduct a social analysis with emphasis on gender issues, reaching the poor, 
and participation of the poor; 
(vi)  prepare  a  poverty  and  social  assessment  paper  per  ADB  guidelines,  in 
coordination with the PRSP and other related assistance, to avoid duplication; 
(vii)  assess women's and men's overall participation in local government structures; 
(viii)  assess  existing  institutional  mechanisms  enabling  the  poor  and  socially 
vulnerable, especially women, to voice their needs and difficulties in accessing 
basic social services; 
(ix)  plan and implement a series of four regional and one provincial stakeholder 
workshops with the team, and record findings of plenary and personal interviews 
with stakeholders; 
(x)  document the perceptions and priorities of stakeholders, including beneficiaries, 
through field visits, and prepare a participation strategy; 
(xi)  using a participatory process, develop a strategic framework matrix for improving 
social aspects of program design, in particular targeting the poor and women,
